<p><b>Boilerplate? Wasn't gulp meant to be as easy to use as possible?</b><br>At this point, I have no idea. Gulp is certainly a powerful, flexible &amp; dynamic way to construct your pipeline, but it's <i>not</i> a small thing to set up, so I made this.<br><br>Features include:<ul><li>Transpiles EcmaScript 2015 to EcmaScript 5 compliant JavaScript using <a href="https://babeljs.io">Babel</a></li><li><a href="http://sass-lang.com/">SASS</a> pre-processing</li><li>Bundling all javascript into one script</li><li>Minification &amp; optimization of:</li><li><ul><li>JavaScript</li><li>CSS (structural optimization via <a href="https://github.com/css/csso">CSSO</a>)</li><li>HTML</li><li>jpeg images</li><li>png images</li><li>GIF images</li><li>Animated GIF images</li><li>SVG vectors</li></ul></li><li>Preserves special comments such as <code>&lt;!--! --&gt;</code> and <code>/*! */</code></li><li>Clean, documented gulpfile.js</li><li>Tries to be lightweight on depedencies (it's not easy)</li><li>`dist/` folder should be ready for deployment after a run of `gulp dist`</li></ul>The pipeline's structure is optimized for single-page applications. You should be loading any page data dynamically. This also makes migrating to a more complex application using a template engine such as <a href="http://handlebarsjs.com/">handlebars</a>.</p>